.cnf\n+mysqldump.cnf\n notify-osd.log\n npm-debug.log\n npm-shrinkwrap.json\n@@ -350,21 +394,26 @@ php_errors.log\n phpcs.xml\n phpcs.xml.dist\n phpinfo.php\n+pm2.log\n routing.yml\n sched_debug\n schedstat\n scsi\n secrets.json\n+secrets.yaml\n+secrets.yml\n security.yml\n sendgrid.env\n services.yml\n settings.inc.php\n settings.local.php\n settings.php\n+sftp.json\n slabinfo\n softirqs\n sslvpn_websession\n sysrq-trigger\n+system.ini\n sysvipc\n thread-self\n Thumbs.db\n@@ -377,8 +426,11 @@ vmstat\n Web.config\n weblogic.xml\n webpack.config.js\n+win.ini\n wp-config-\n wp-config.\n wp-config_\n+yarn-debug.log\n+yarn-error.log\n yarn.lock\n zoneinfo\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Review gitignore templates for adding to restrictes-files or lfi data files\n<!--\nFor help and support please go here:\n- https://security.stackexchange.com/questions/tagged/owasp-crs\n\nAsk general usage questions and participate in discussions on the CRS:\n- https://groups.google.com/a/owasp.org/g/modsecurity-core-rule-set-project\n-->\n### Motivation\n\n<!-- A clear and concise description of what the motivation for the -->\n<!-- new feature is, and what problem it is solving. -->\nThere are plenty of files, per language, that you should normally never commit to a git repo in https://github.com/github/gitignore.\n\n### Proposed solution\n\n<!-- A clear and concise description of the feature you would like -->\n<!-- to add, and how it solves the motivating problem. -->\nI think we can make this work for us by:\n- [ ] parse and understand which files that might have sensitive content\n- [ ] update the list of file names, if possible in an automated way\n\n### Alternatives\n\n<!-- A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions -->\n<!-- or features you've considered, and why you're proposed solution is -->\n<!-- better. -->\n\n### Additional context\n\n<!-- Add any other context or screenshots about the feature request -->\n<!-- here. -->\n\n", "hints_text": "Will this do: https://chatgpt.com/share/68d1154f-0e8c-8000-9be3-114024374c9b\n@Xhoenix Looks like the download link is no longer working, do you still have that file on you?\n\nI asked ChatGPT to re-generate the download and I can see that it's missing most entries just from skimming through the generated file.\n\n[missing_gitignore_candidates_v2.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/22999769/missing_gitignore_candidates_v2.txt)\n```\n#*#\n*.crt\n*.csr\n*.der\n*.jks\n*.key\n*.log\n*.p12\n*.pem\n*.pfx\n*.pyc\n*.pyo\n*.swo\n*.swp\n*.tfstate*\n*~\n.Python\n.azure/\n.cache/\n.cache/*\n.classpath\n.coverage\n.credentials\n.dockerignore\n.env.*\n.env.development\n.env.example\n.env.local\n.env.production\n.env.template\n.idea/\n.ipynb_checkpoints/\n.npmrc\n.pass\n.project\n.pytest_cache/\n.secrets\n.settings/\n.terraform.lock.hcl\n.terraform/\n.tfstate\n.venv\n.venv/\n.vscode/\n.yarnrc\n.yarnrc.yml\n__pycache__/\nbin/\nbuild/\ncomposer.lock\nconfig/*.key\nconfig/*.pem\ncoverage.xml\ncoverage/\ncredentials.json\ndebug.log\ndesktop.ini\ndist/\nenv/\njspm_packages/\nlogs/\nnode_modules/\nnpm-debug.log*\nobj/\nout/\npm2.log\npm2.pid\npnpm-lock.yaml\nsecrets.json\nsecrets.yaml\nsecrets.yml\nsensitive.env\ntarget/\nvendor/\nvenv/\nyarn-debug.log*\nyarn-error.log*\n```\n@Xhoenix Thanks\n\nAs I've been digging through these lists, I feel we should be taking a much more generic approach to blocking restricted files then we do now. I have a few ideas but I can easily see the amount of false positives rising substantially so for now I'll open an issue and update the restricted files/file extensions.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Will this do: https://chatgpt.com/share/68d1154f-0e8c-8000-9be3-114024374c9b\n@Xhoenix Looks like the download link is no longer working, do you still have that file on you?\n\nI asked ChatGPT to re-generate the download and I can see that it's missing most entries just from skimming through the generated file.\n\n[missing_gitignore_candidates_v2.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/22999769/missing_gitignore_candidates_v2.txt)\n```\n#*#\n*.crt\n*.csr\n*.der\n*.jks\n*.key\n*.log\n*.p12\n*.pem\n*.pfx\n*.pyc\n*.pyo\n*.swo\n*.swp\n*.tfstate*\n*~\n.Python\n.azure/\n.cache/\n.cache/*\n.classpath\n.coverage\n.credentials\n.dockerignore\n.env.*\n.env.development\n.env.example\n.env.local\n.env.production\n.env.template\n.idea/\n.ipynb_checkpoints/\n.npmrc\n.pass\n.project\n.pytest_cache/\n.secrets\n.settings/\n.terraform.lock.hcl\n.terraform/\n.tfstate\n.venv\n.venv/\n.vscode/\n.yarnrc\n.yarnrc.yml\n__pycache__/\nbin/\nbuild/\ncomposer.lock\nconfig/*.key\nconfig/*.pem\ncoverage.xml\ncoverage/\ncredentials.json\ndebug.log\ndesktop.ini\ndist/\nenv/\njspm_packages/\nlogs/\nnode_modules/\nnpm-debug.log*\nobj/\nout/\npm2.log\npm2.pid\npnpm-lock.yaml\nsecrets.json\nsecrets.yaml\nsecrets.yml\nsensitive.env\ntarget/\nvendor/\nvenv/\nyarn-debug.log*\nyarn-error.log*\n```\n@Xhoenix Thanks\n\nAs I've been digging through these lists, I feel we should be taking a much more generic approach to blocking restricted files then we do now. I have a few ideas but I can easily see the amount of false positives rising substantially so for now I'll open an issue and update the restricted files/file extensions.\n@fzipi \n\n> update the list of file names, if possible in an automated way\n\nI'm not sure if this is possible, in most lists I've seen online (Including this one) I've seen many entries that don't make much sense to add to CRS. I think we should refactor the rules to avoid the fragmentation of `restricted-files.data`, `lfi-os-files.data`, and `restricted-uploads.data` and merge them into one regex assembly file for better flexibility on what to block. We shouldn't blindly add each and every single entry to keep any false positive risk to a minimum.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/34db29b174125a9b434443fdb1b317b7482e9114", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/52e9c01ce6758adf42e8ea8cafed70337db81cc7", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/014f82b52b914ccc956deab61735e23d0f5ad928", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/61025f95d8228af6c0b56e0bff1750962fdd9f52", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/124dd78b6e6cebe98c130dabfb61ba0b45c2faff", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/ab195e2e4c77ca142e1f253d97e2bd7f1ffe948e", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/635f69ae0e138474518b522c8e537bb55250a751", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/c361827ab77372e59b893d8bb49752665058cfab", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/df78319cd64d7c74820b095a11e0d48d6c584444", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/51a3dc12af21348c0921a33dbe34b9d110e71b91", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/92b5dc8d5396b3d2fbfa44a056be5d0c42816904", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/8836ec8d70f0e5eca9c54a76eef31a48796a29b5", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/1c96d427586bd839b54d2baed1dbee7c3c4a4f82", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/734b011f99db0990573ff474d67c7f384c8d569b"], "created_at": "2025-10-21T04:48:07Z"}
{"repo": "coreruleset/coreruleset", "pull_number": 4298, "instance_id": "coreruleset__coreruleset-4298", "issue_numbers": [4251], "base_commit": "1fbd77e79fbea55c1664d9d3f652e26d6e05bdca", "patch": "diff --git a/crs-setup.conf.example b/crs-setup.conf.example\nindex 883a97d8b2..bbe974caff 100644\n--- a/crs-setup.conf.example\n+++ b/crs-setup.conf.example\n@@ -586,7 +586,7 @@ SecDefaultAction \"phase:2,log,auditlog,pass\"\n # [ Basic ]\n # Includes deprecated headers and headers with known security risks. Always\n # forbidden.\n-# Default: /content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/\n+# Default: /content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/ /expect/\n #\n # /content-encoding/\n #   Used to list any encodings that have been applied to the original payload.\n@@ -615,6 +615,10 @@ SecDefaultAction \"phase:2,log,auditlog,pass\"\n # /x-middleware-subrequest/\n #   CVE-2025-29927 (Next.js)\n #\n+# /expect/\n+#   Blocking this header prevents Expect-based desync attacks\n+#   https://portswigger.net/research/http1-must-die#expect-based-desync-attacks\n+#\n # Uncomment this rule to change the default.\n #SecAction \\\n #    \"id:900250,\\\n@@ -624,7 +628,7 @@ SecDefaultAction \"phase:2,log,auditlog,pass\"\n #    nolog,\\\n #    tag:'OWASP_CRS',\\\n #    ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.20.0-dev',\\\n-#    setvar:'tx.restricted_headers_basic=/content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/'\"\n+#    setvar:'tx.restricted_headers_basic=/content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/ /expect/'\"\n #\n # [ Extended ]\n # Includes deprecated headers that are still in use (so false positives are\ndiff --git a/rules/REQUEST-901-INITIALIZATION.conf b/rules/REQUEST-901-INITIALIZATION.conf\nindex 1fba2fc72f..da489c81c5 100644\n--- a/rules/REQUEST-901-INITIALIZATION.conf\n+++ b/rules/REQUEST-901-INITIALIZATION.conf\n@@ -237,7 +237,7 @@ SecRule &TX:restricted_headers_basic \"@eq 0\" \\\n     nolog,\\\n     tag:'OWASP_CRS',\\\n     ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.20.0-dev',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.restricted_headers_basic=/content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/'\"\n+    setvar:'tx.restricted_headers_basic=/content-encoding/ /proxy/ /lock-token/ /content-range/ /if/ /x-http-method-override/ /x-http-method/ /x-method-override/ /x-middleware-subrequest/ /expect/'\"\n \n # Default HTTP policy: restricted_headers_extended (rule 900255 in crs-setup.conf)\n SecRule &TX:restricted_headers_extended \"@eq 0\" \\\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Block `Expect` header\n### Motivation\n\nReading https://portswigger.net/research/http1-must-die, it seems clear that the `Expect` header is a very big problem with HTTP/1.1. It's very rarely used intentionally and especially reverse proxy setups are vulnerable to desync attacks.\n\n### Proposed solution\n\nAdd `Expect` to the list of restricted headers `restricted_headers_basic`.\n\n", "hints_text": "Will this break a lot of web applications? Specifically, _non_-HTTP/2 clients doing things like file uploads, WebDAV actions, etc.? Thinking about applications like NextCloud and friends \ud83e\udd14 \n\nIt _feels_ like `Expect` - `Continue` is a fairly fundamental part of HTTP, for CRS to start _blocking by default_.\n\nIf there's a tl;dr of the James Kettle thing to argue otherwise, that would be great to see here as a counter-argument. (portswigger.net seems to be offline at the moment\u2026)\nI have no idea TBH. According to MDN:\n\n> None of the more common browsers send the Expect header, but some clients (command-line tools) do so by default.\n\nWe could put the header into the extended list (PL2) but I feel like this is such gaping hole that we need to block at PL1.\n\n@EsadCetiner @azurit @michelamarie do you see the `Expect` header on your servers?\n@theseion I don't see any reference in my audit log just from doing a quick grep, most of my clients are HTTP/2 so I might not be the best person to ask. At least according to [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Headers/Expect) that header should be uncommon.\n\nI'll create a rule that checks for the header and let you know what I find, if it's used by Nextcloud then I'll find out real quick.\n> \u2026some clients (command-line tools) do so by default.\n\nThat tracks. curl file uploads definitely do use this mechanism (presumably any libcurl-based clients also), and it does wait for the correct response.\nThis is a really interesting _(and potentially terrifying)_ issue. I will configure a few environments to capture requests containing an Expect request header, and report back what I find.\n\nJust to make sure we have the details correct on the nature of this threat, as identified by the blog author, it appears that, _(like the other attacks demonstrated in the cited Portswigger blog post)_:\n* These vulnerabilities involving Expect only apply to requests, where the environment is fronted by a reverse-proxy that opens connections to back-end servers in HTTP 1.x. \n* Requests to front-ends can use HTTP/2, or HTTP 1.x in order for exploits involving Expect to be successful _(at least in many cases)_., as long as the connection to the back-end uses HTTP 1.x. I imagine a lot of reverse proxies are configured this way _(h2 front-end, and using HTTP 1.1 to the back-end nodes)_, in addition to the CDNs and other examples given in the blog post.\n\nDo I have those conditions correct?\nMostly:\n- I wouldn't dismiss potential attacks without reverse proxy. Reverse proxies are just easy to attack this way\n- HTTP/2 does not have an `Expect` header, according to https://www.iana.org/assignments/message-headers/message-headers.xhtml, And the way HTTP/2 works doesn't allow for the `Content-Type`, `Transfer-Encoding` shenanigans presented in the blog post. Potentially there's a way, but it would be significantly harder I believe with an HTTP/2 frontend connection. Still, the critical path is the backend connection, as stated in the post.\nThanks, and fair enough. It's true, we should not assume these vulnerabilities do not exist in environments without a reverse proxy.\n\nThanks for the confirmation about Expect in HTTP/2 as well -- that's what I thought, but I could not find confirmation of it when I briefly checked the [RFC for it](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110#field.expect) and a few other sources. The RFC for Expect mentions HTTP 1.1 \"or later\" -- I suppose they put that there in case another revision to 1.x was to be released in the future. \ud83e\udd37\u200d\u2640\ufe0f \nHi @EsadCetiner \n\nDid you find out if you have any `Expect` headers in your environment?\n\n> I'll create a rule that checks for the header and let you know what I find, if it's used by Nextcloud then I'll find out real quick.\n\nI'll open a PR if we think this header is not used in a legitimate way.\n\n@franbuehler I've been testing for about two weeks and didn't get any hits so far. All of my clients are modern so I'm not sure if older clients make use of this header.\nThank you very much @EsadCetiner. This sounds very promising!\nI haven't seen any requests for this header on the machines I've been monitoring for it on either. No malicious requests that include it have been found so far either, which surprised me slightly. I may put a rule checking for it in a couple more environments that get more traffic if I have a chance.\nThanks @EsadCetiner, @michelamarie. Let's go ahead with a PR. @franbuehler, would you take this one?\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Will this break a lot of web applications? Specifically, _non_-HTTP/2 clients doing things like file uploads, WebDAV actions, etc.? Thinking about applications like NextCloud and friends \ud83e\udd14 \n\nIt _feels_ like `Expect` - `Continue` is a fairly fundamental part of HTTP, for CRS to start _blocking by default_.\n\nIf there's a tl;dr of the James Kettle thing to argue otherwise, that would be great to see here as a counter-argument. (portswigger.net seems to be offline at the moment\u2026)\nI have no idea TBH. According to MDN:\n\n> None of the more common browsers send the Expect header, but some clients (command-line tools) do so by default.\n\nWe could put the header into the extended list (PL2) but I feel like this is such gaping hole that we need to block at PL1.\n\n@EsadCetiner @azurit @michelamarie do you see the `Expect` header on your servers?\n@theseion I don't see any reference in my audit log just from doing a quick grep, most of my clients are HTTP/2 so I might not be the best person to ask. At least according to [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Headers/Expect) that header should be uncommon.\n\nI'll create a rule that checks for the header and let you know what I find, if it's used by Nextcloud then I'll find out real quick.\n> \u2026some clients (command-line tools) do so by default.\n\nThat tracks. curl file uploads definitely do use this mechanism (presumably any libcurl-based clients also), and it does wait for the correct response.\nThis is a really interesting _(and potentially terrifying)_ issue. I will configure a few environments to capture requests containing an Expect request header, and report back what I find.\n\nJust to make sure we have the details correct on the nature of this threat, as identified by the blog author, it appears that, _(like the other attacks demonstrated in the cited Portswigger blog post)_:\n* These vulnerabilities involving Expect only apply to requests, where the environment is fronted by a reverse-proxy that opens connections to back-end servers in HTTP 1.x. \n* Requests to front-ends can use HTTP/2, or HTTP 1.x in order for exploits involving Expect to be successful _(at least in many cases)_., as long as the connection to the back-end uses HTTP 1.x. I imagine a lot of reverse proxies are configured this way _(h2 front-end, and using HTTP 1.1 to the back-end nodes)_, in addition to the CDNs and other examples given in the blog post.\n\nDo I have those conditions correct?\nMostly:\n- I wouldn't dismiss potential attacks without reverse proxy. Reverse proxies are just easy to attack this way\n- HTTP/2 does not have an `Expect` header, according to https://www.iana.org/assignments/message-headers/message-headers.xhtml, And the way HTTP/2 works doesn't allow for the `Content-Type`, `Transfer-Encoding` shenanigans presented in the blog post. Potentially there's a way, but it would be significantly harder I believe with an HTTP/2 frontend connection. Still, the critical path is the backend connection, as stated in the post.\nThanks, and fair enough. It's true, we should not assume these vulnerabilities do not exist in environments without a reverse proxy.\n\nThanks for the confirmation about Expect in HTTP/2 as well -- that's what I thought, but I could not find confirmation of it when I briefly checked the [RFC for it](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110#field.expect) and a few other sources. The RFC for Expect mentions HTTP 1.1 \"or later\" -- I suppose they put that there in case another revision to 1.x was to be released in the future. \ud83e\udd37\u200d\u2640\ufe0f \nHi @EsadCetiner \n\nDid you find out if you have any `Expect` headers in your environment?\n\n> I'll create a rule that checks for the header and let you know what I find, if it's used by Nextcloud then I'll find out real quick.\n\nI'll open a PR if we think this header is not used in a legitimate way.\n\n@franbuehler I've been testing for about two weeks and didn't get any hits so far. All of my clients are modern so I'm not sure if older clients make use of this header.\nThank you very much @EsadCetiner. This sounds very promising!\nI haven't seen any requests for this header on the machines I've been monitoring for it on either. No malicious requests that include it have been found so far either, which surprised me slightly. I may put a rule checking for it in a couple more environments that get more traffic if I have a chance.\nThanks @EsadCetiner, @michelamarie. Let's go ahead with a PR. @franbuehler, would you take this one?\nAfter updating to block the `Expect` header, I had a few people affected. They both used .NET (`System.Net.HttpWebRequest`). They reported the solution of setting `ServicePointManager.Expect100Continue = false;` (see https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.net.servicepointmanager.expect100continue?view=net-10.0). I figured I'd add it here for anything else having the same issue.\n@ssigwart Thank you!\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/8ee1c4dd1a750247467933703bcfd51785b36175", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/a208313c2120f5982a94d0a5e22acfc45367ea36"], "created_at": "2025-10-20T11:19:00Z"}
{"repo": "coreruleset/coreruleset", "pull_number": 4338, "instance_id": "coreruleset__coreruleset-4338", "issue_numbers": [4320], "base_commit": "0d9355b44b3fa7d2f40635ec4417ec7ad5933d91", "patch": "diff --git a/rules/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE.conf b/rules/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE.conf\nindex c33035b7ff..ade6f51134 100644\n--- a/rules/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE.conf\n+++ b/rules/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE.conf\n@@ -756,6 +756,10 @@ SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@rx \\ba[\\\"\n # that affect the behavior of the web server, possibly causing remote\n # code execution.\n #\n+# The inverted chained rule enforces a word boundary for some entries that are prone to\n+# being detected as false positives. This can't be enforced for all entries since some are intentionally meant to match permutations.\n+#\n+#\n SecRule FILES|REQUEST_HEADERS:X-Filename|REQUEST_HEADERS:X_Filename|REQUEST_HEADERS:X-File-Name \"@pmFromFile restricted-upload.data\" \\\n     \"id:932180,\\\n     phase:2,\\\n@@ -774,8 +778,11 @@ SecRule FILES|REQUEST_HEADERS:X-Filename|REQUEST_HEADERS:X_Filename|REQUEST_HEAD\n     tag:'capec/1000/152/248/88',\\\n     ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',\\\n     severity:'CRITICAL',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.rce_score=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.inbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}'\"\n+    chain\"\n+    SecRule MATCHED_VARS \"!@rx (?i)(?:\\.boto|buddyinfo|mtrr|acpi|zoneinfo)\\B\" \\\n+        \"t:none,\\\n+        setvar:'tx.rce_score=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}',\\\n+        setvar:'tx.inbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}'\"\n \n \n # [ Windows command injection ]\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE/932180.yaml b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE/932180.yaml\nindex 0da30b60d3..941075da34 100644\n--- a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE/932180.yaml\n+++ b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-932-APPLICATION-ATTACK-RCE/932180.yaml\n@@ -1,6 +1,6 @@\n ---\n meta:\n-  author: \"Franziska B\u00fchler, azurit\"\n+  author: \"Franziska B\u00fchler, azurit, Esad Cetiner\"\n   description: \"Restricted File Upload Attempt\"\n rule_id: 932180\n tests:\n@@ -80,3 +80,165 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 4\n+    desc: \"False Positive: Matching substring `.boto`\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: abc.botox.jpg\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 5\n+    desc: \"False Positive: Matching substring `mtrr`\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: amtrra.jpg\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 6\n+    desc: \"False Positive: Matching substring `acpi`\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: JACpic.jpg\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 7\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block uploading `.boto`\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: .boto\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 8\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block uploading `mtrr`(/proc/mtrr)\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: mtrr\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 9\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block uploading `acpi`\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: acpi\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 10\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Match permutations of config files\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: wp-config.php\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 11\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Match permutations of config files\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: wp-config-php.bak\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n+  - test_id: 12\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Match permutations of config files\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+            Host: localhost\n+            Proxy-Connection: keep-alive\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            X-Filename: wp-config_php.txt\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get\"\n+          version: HTTP/1.1\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [932180]\n", "problem_statement": "Rule 932180 FP on Filename Substring\n### Description\n\nRule 932180 triggers for substrings in filenames. See `curl` examples below.\n\n### How to reproduce the misbehavior (-> curl call)\n\nThis example is likely a user's initials (JAC).\n```sh\necho \"contents\" | curl -X POST -F \"file1=@-;filename=JACpic.jpg;type=text/plain\" -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org/\n```\n\n```\n932180 PL1 Restricted File Upload Attempt\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 5)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=5, detection=5, per_pl=5-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=5, PHPI=0, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=5)\n```\n\nThis one triggers  due to `boto`.\n```sh\necho \"contents\" | curl -X POST -F \"file1=@-;filename=abc.botox.jpg;type=text/plain\" -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org/\n```\n\n```\n932180 PL1 Restricted File Upload Attempt\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 5)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=5, detection=5, per_pl=5-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=5, PHPI=0, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=5)\n```\n\nThis triggers due to `mtrr`\n```sh\necho \"contents\" | curl -X POST -F \"file1=@-;filename=amtrra.jpg;type=text/plain\" -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org/\n```\n\n```\n932180 PL1 Restricted File Upload Attempt\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 5)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=5, detection=5, per_pl=5-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=5, PHPI=0, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=5)\n```\n\n### Your Environment\n\n* CRS version (e.g., v3.3.4): 4.18.0\n* Paranoia level setting (e.g. PL1) : PL1\n* ModSecurity version (e.g., 2.9.6): 3.0.14\n* Web Server and version or cloud provider / CDN (e.g., Apache httpd 2.4.54): Nginx 1.26\n* Operating System and version: Amazon Linux 2\n\n### Confirmation\n\n[X] I have removed any personal data (email addresses, IP addresses,\n    passwords, domain names) from any logs posted.\n\n", "hints_text": "@ssigwart Thanks for the report, I can see the issue is that we're trimming the entries being imported into `restricted-upload.data`.\n\n@coreruleset/core-developers Does anyone know why we trim the entries in `restricted-upload.data` when importing them from `restricted-files.data`, and `lfi-os-files.data`? For instance with `/proc/mtrr` we're shortening it to just `mtrr` which increases the chances of false positives.\nThe idea is to prevent files with these names from being uploaded at all, since an attacker might be able to move them later or otherwise obfuscate the path. For example, if we matched `proc/mtrr`, a file named `mtrr` could still be uploaded. That being said, paths like `.boto` don't have a prefix in `restricted-files.data` either.\n\nI think the bigger issue is the way we use `@pmFromFile` there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.\n@theseion\n\n> I think the bigger issue is the way we use @pmFromFile there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.\n\nAgreed, but how do you suggest fixing the way we use the `@pmFromFile` operator to prevent false positives like this? Unless I'm missing something, the boundary provided by that operator won't work for this case. The only other solution is to switch to a regex which iirc is heavier than the `@pmFromFile` operator.\nAbsolutely. One thing, which we've done before, I believe, could be to add a chain rule that runs the more precise regex only when `@pmFromFile` found a match in the first place. The chain rule could then also use a macro for the match found in the start rule, so we would't have to create a regex that can match every entry, e.g., `@rx %{MATCH_DATA}\\b`. Of course, using a macro would require the regex to be compiled for each run, but as runs should be less frequent, maybe it could work.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "@ssigwart Thanks for the report, I can see the issue is that we're trimming the entries being imported into `restricted-upload.data`.\n\n@coreruleset/core-developers Does anyone know why we trim the entries in `restricted-upload.data` when importing them from `restricted-files.data`, and `lfi-os-files.data`? For instance with `/proc/mtrr` we're shortening it to just `mtrr` which increases the chances of false positives.\nThe idea is to prevent files with these names from being uploaded at all, since an attacker might be able to move them later or otherwise obfuscate the path. For example, if we matched `proc/mtrr`, a file named `mtrr` could still be uploaded. That being said, paths like `.boto` don't have a prefix in `restricted-files.data` either.\n\nI think the bigger issue is the way we use `@pmFromFile` there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.\n@theseion\n\n> I think the bigger issue is the way we use @pmFromFile there, as it produceds substring matches, which isn't what we want, IMO.\n\nAgreed, but how do you suggest fixing the way we use the `@pmFromFile` operator to prevent false positives like this? Unless I'm missing something, the boundary provided by that operator won't work for this case. The only other solution is to switch to a regex which iirc is heavier than the `@pmFromFile` operator.\nAbsolutely. One thing, which we've done before, I believe, could be to add a chain rule that runs the more precise regex only when `@pmFromFile` found a match in the first place. The chain rule could then also use a macro for the match found in the start rule, so we would't have to create a regex that can match every entry, e.g., `@rx %{MATCH_DATA}\\b`. Of course, using a macro would require the regex to be compiled for each run, but as runs should be less frequent, maybe it could work.\n@theseion I've tried using a macro within the `@rx` operator as you suggested but it's being interpreted as a regex by Apache and outright rejected for NGINX so that won't work.\n\nI did come up with a similar solution however in this PR #4338 \n@ssigwart I've opened a PR at #4338 which should resolve this issue.\n@EsadCetiner that's nasty. Would you mind opening an issue with ModSecurity to adjust the documentation / create a fix?\nThanks, @EsadCetiner. The PR has exactly the ones I have an issue with here, so it would definitely help me. If this gets merged, I can create PRs for other common ones that come up. However, I wonder if there's a more general way to solve it. Scanning https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/blob/main/rules/restricted-upload.data, I can think of a few that are plausible:\n- `buddyinfo` - `BuddyInfoSession.pdf`\n- `zoneinfo` - `FunZoneInfo.pdf`\n@ssigwart Thanks, I've added those entries as well\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/081c168a80ea8e9b2de000f88d6686f2ae3e8728", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/6e1aea78c05dadcb6e4fb6192c83c4464dbf959f", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/d275d7187af140a5f01f844070e264611f7a6191", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/f2b36caa0dae01be99a4887aab075afe8168e0d0", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/921fadf9d5135d3cfefc6d7f15d7f9337c386977", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/031097d0ba65e4e6f10ce017ee972da0aa4eb8d6"], "created_at": "2025-11-14T04:09:27Z"}
{"repo": "coreruleset/coreruleset", "pull_number": 4340, "instance_id": "coreruleset__coreruleset-4340", "issue_numbers": [4335], "base_commit": "262cd7b7df57cddbbc755e7b56e0c71615aa376c", "patch": "diff --git a/regex-assembly/933160.ra b/regex-assembly/933160.ra\nindex e63c612e4b..9c8ab4d7ab 100644\n--- a/regex-assembly/933160.ra\n+++ b/regex-assembly/933160.ra\n@@ -41,6 +41,7 @@ md5\n mkdir\n opendir\n passthru\n+phpinfo\n popen\n printf\n readfile\n@@ -53,9 +54,11 @@ usort\n ##! English words, or potential snippets of them, are added here to perform a regex match.\n ##! Compared to the parallel match performed by 933150, fewer false positives will be generated.\n exp\n+intval\n ord\n prev\n stat\n substr\n system\n unlink\n+unserialize\ndiff --git a/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf b/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf\nindex 639169fb27..39c3af59db 100644\n--- a/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf\n+++ b/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf\n@@ -279,13 +279,13 @@ SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@rx (?:bzi\n # The list of PHP functions is divided into four groups of varying attack/false positive risk.\n # Four separate rules are used to detect these groups of functions:\n #\n-# - Rule 933150: ~237 words highly common to PHP injection payloads and extremely rare in\n+# - Rule 933150: ~234 words highly common to PHP injection payloads and extremely rare in\n #\t\tnatural language or other contexts.\n #\t\tExamples: 'base64_decode', 'file_get_contents'.\n #\t\tThese words are detected as a match directly using @pmFromFile.\n #\t\tFunction names are defined in php-function-names-933150.data\n #\n-# - Rule 933160: ~36 words which are common in PHP code, but have a higher chance to cause\n+# - Rule 933160: ~39 words which are common in PHP code, but have a higher chance to cause\n #\t\tfalse positives in natural language or other contexts.\n #\t\tExamples: 'chr', 'eval'.\n #\t\tTo mitigate false positives, a regexp looks for PHP function syntax, e.g. 'eval()'.\n@@ -312,8 +312,10 @@ SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@rx (?:bzi\n #\n # Rule 933150 contains a small list of function names which are highly indicative of a PHP\n # injection attack, for example 'base64_decode'.\n-# We block these function names outright, without using a complex regexp or chain.\n-# This could make the detection a bit more robust against possible bypasses.\n+# The rule uses a chained rule to require parentheses after function names.\n+# This prevents false positives from substring matches (e.g., \"intval\" in \"PaintValdosta\").\n+# Functions that commonly appear as English words/substrings are handled by rule 933160\n+# with stricter regex-based function call syntax validation.\n #\n SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|REQUEST_FILENAME|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@pmFromFile php-function-names-933150.data\" \\\n     \"id:933150,\\\n@@ -333,8 +335,11 @@ SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|REQUEST_FILENAME|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|X\n     tag:'capec/1000/152/242',\\\n     ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.23.0-dev',\\\n     severity:'CRITICAL',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.php_injection_score=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.inbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}'\"\n+    chain\"\n+    SecRule MATCHED_VARS \"@pm ( )\" \\\n+        \"t:none,\\\n+        setvar:'tx.php_injection_score=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}',\\\n+        setvar:'tx.inbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.critical_anomaly_score}'\"\n \n \n #\n@@ -368,7 +373,7 @@ SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|REQUEST_FILENAME|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|X\n # (consult https://coreruleset.org/docs/development/regex_assembly/ for details):\n #   crs-toolchain regex update 933160\n #\n-SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|REQUEST_FILENAME|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@rx (?i)\\b\\(?[\\\"']*(?:assert(?:_options)?|c(?:hr|reate_function)|e(?:val|x(?:ec|p))|f(?:ile(?:group)?|open|puts)|glob|i(?:mage(?:gif|(?:jpe|pn)g|wbmp|xbm)|s_a)|m(?:d5|kdir)|o(?:pendir|rd)|p(?:assthru|open|r(?:intf|ev))|r(?:eadfile|trim)|s(?:t(?:rip_tags|at)|ubstr|ystem)|tmpfile|u(?:n(?:pac|lin)k|sort))(?:/(?:\\*.*?\\*/|/[^\\n\\r]*)|#[^\\n\\r]*|[\\s\\x0b\\\"])*[\\\"']*\\)?[\\s\\x0b]*\\([^\\)]*\\)\" \\\n+SecRule REQUEST_COOKIES|REQUEST_COOKIES_NAMES|REQUEST_FILENAME|ARGS_NAMES|ARGS|XML:/* \"@rx (?i)\\b\\(?[\\\"']*(?:assert(?:_options)?|c(?:hr|reate_function)|e(?:val|x(?:ec|p))|f(?:ile(?:group)?|open|puts)|glob|i(?:mage(?:gif|(?:jpe|pn)g|wbmp|xbm)|s_a|ntval)|m(?:d5|kdir)|o(?:pendir|rd)|p(?:assthru|hpinfo|open|r(?:intf|ev))|r(?:eadfile|trim)|s(?:t(?:rip_tags|at)|ubstr|ystem)|tmpfile|u(?:n(?:(?:pac|lin)k|serialize)|sort))(?:/(?:\\*.*?\\*/|/[^\\n\\r]*)|#[^\\n\\r]*|[\\s\\x0b\\\"])*[\\\"']*\\)?[\\s\\x0b]*\\([^\\)]*\\)\" \\\n     \"id:933160,\\\n     phase:2,\\\n     block,\\\ndiff --git a/rules/php-function-names-933150.data b/rules/php-function-names-933150.data\nindex adc6afc2b0..c4b2573f6a 100644\n--- a/rules/php-function-names-933150.data\n+++ b/rules/php-function-names-933150.data\n@@ -98,7 +98,6 @@ imagegd2\n ini_get\n ini_get_all\n ini_set\n-intval\n iptcembed\n is_array\n is_dir\n@@ -149,7 +148,6 @@ pg_prepare\n pg_query\n php_strip_whitespace\n php_uname\n-phpinfo\n phpversion\n posix_getegid\n posix_geteuid\n@@ -231,7 +229,6 @@ strtoupper\n uasort\n ucfirst\n uksort\n-unserialize\n urldecode\n urlencode\n var_dump\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933150.yaml b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933150.yaml\nindex 497ce73c10..9e18cde878 100644\n--- a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933150.yaml\n+++ b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933150.yaml\n@@ -4,22 +4,6 @@ meta:\n rule_id: 933150\n tests:\n   - test_id: 1\n-    desc: phpinfo\n-    stages:\n-      - input:\n-          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n-          headers:\n-            Host: localhost\n-            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n-            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n-          method: GET\n-          port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get/phpinfo\"\n-          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n-        output:\n-          log:\n-            expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 2\n     desc: base64_decode\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -30,12 +14,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get/base64_decode\"\n+          uri: \"/get/?test=base64_decode()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 3\n+  - test_id: 2\n     desc: base64_decode mixed case\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -46,12 +30,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?base64_deCOde\"\n+          uri: \"/get?base64_deCOde()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 4\n+  - test_id: 3\n     desc: bzdecompress\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -62,12 +46,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=bzdecomprEss\"\n+          uri: \"/get?foo=bzdecomprEss()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 5\n+  - test_id: 4\n     desc: call_user_func\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -78,12 +62,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOcall_user_func\"\n+          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOcall_user_func()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 6\n+  - test_id: 5\n     desc: fsockopen\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -94,12 +78,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOfsockopen\"\n+          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOfsockopen()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 7\n+  - test_id: 6\n     desc: gzdecode\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -110,12 +94,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOgzdecode\"\n+          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOgzdecode()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 8\n+  - test_id: 7\n     desc: GzInFlAtE\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -126,28 +110,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOGzInFlAtE\"\n-          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n-        output:\n-          log:\n-            expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 9\n-    desc: pHpInFo mixed case\n-    stages:\n-      - input:\n-          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n-          headers:\n-            Host: localhost\n-            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n-            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n-          method: GET\n-          port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOpHpInFo\"\n+          uri: \"/get?foo=FOOGzInFlAtE()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 10\n+  - test_id: 8\n     desc: gzuncompress\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -158,12 +126,12 @@ tests:\n             Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n           method: GET\n           port: 80\n-          uri: \"/get?I%20don%27t%20like%20gzuncompress\"\n+          uri: \"/get?test=I%20don%27t%20like%20gzuncompress/*comment*/()\"\n           version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 11\n+  - test_id: 9\n     desc: fsockopen\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -178,7 +146,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 12\n+  - test_id: 10\n     desc: posix_getpwuiD\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -194,11 +162,11 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 13\n+  - test_id: 11\n     desc: shell_exec\n     stages:\n       - input:\n-          data: Shell%5fexec=bla\n+          data: test=Shell%5fexec=(bla)\n           dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n           headers:\n             Host: localhost\n@@ -211,11 +179,11 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 14\n+  - test_id: 12\n     desc: ZlIb_DeCoDe\n     stages:\n       - input:\n-          data: ZlIb%5fDeCoDe=bla\n+          data: test=ZlIb%5fDeCoDe=(bla)\n           dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n           headers:\n             Host: localhost\n@@ -228,7 +196,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 15\n+  - test_id: 13\n     desc: get_defined_functions\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -245,7 +213,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 16\n+  - test_id: 14\n     desc: get_defined_vars\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -262,7 +230,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 17\n+  - test_id: 15\n     desc: |\n       PHP function call in body, mixed case.\n       payload: curl_iNit()\n@@ -281,7 +249,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 18\n+  - test_id: 16\n     desc: |\n       PHP function call in body\n       payload: posix_getegid()\n@@ -300,7 +268,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 19\n+  - test_id: 17\n     desc: |\n       PHP function call in body, mixed case\n       payload: Print_r()\n@@ -319,7 +287,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 20\n+  - test_id: 18\n     desc: |\n       PHP function call in body.\n       payload: strrev()\n@@ -338,7 +306,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 21\n+  - test_id: 19\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: the files (yep)\n@@ -356,7 +324,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 22\n+  - test_id: 20\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test, exec should be followed by parenthesis\n       payload: exec (\n@@ -374,7 +342,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 23\n+  - test_id: 21\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: executor()\n@@ -392,7 +360,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 24\n+  - test_id: 22\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: cheval($foo)\n@@ -410,7 +378,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 25\n+  - test_id: 23\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: audiofile($foo)\n@@ -428,7 +396,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 26\n+  - test_id: 24\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: the system is down()\n@@ -446,7 +414,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 27\n+  - test_id: 25\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test\n       payload: ecosystem()\n@@ -464,7 +432,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 28\n+  - test_id: 26\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test, function doesn't exist\n       payload: systems()\n@@ -482,7 +450,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 29\n+  - test_id: 27\n     desc: |\n       False Positive test, function doesn't exist\n       payload: system something()\n@@ -500,7 +468,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 30\n+  - test_id: 28\n     desc: \"Snippets of English words (like `prev`) should not be matched, requiring regex match with word boundaries (e.g. 933160)\"\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -516,7 +484,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 31\n+  - test_id: 29\n     desc: \"Snippets of English words (like `exp`) should not be matched, requiring regex match with word boundaries (e.g. 933160)\"\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -532,7 +500,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 32\n+  - test_id: 30\n     desc: |\n       PHP mixed case function call with space, LF between ().\n       payload: file_ExistS (\\n\\n)\n@@ -550,7 +518,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 33\n+  - test_id: 31\n     desc: |\n       False positive with filename matching `fopen`\n     stages:\n@@ -567,7 +535,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 34\n+  - test_id: 32\n     desc: |\n       SEO Framework false positive\n       matching 'strip_tags' in 'title_strip_tags'\n@@ -585,7 +553,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 35\n+  - test_id: 33\n     desc: False positive with SprintForTheCause matching printf\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -601,7 +569,7 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n-  - test_id: 36\n+  - test_id: 34\n     desc: Don't block printf function (Handled by 933160)\n     stages:\n       - input:\n@@ -617,3 +585,83 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             no_expect_ids: [933150]\n+  - test_id: 35\n+    desc: \"False Positive: `unserialize` substring false positive\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=A%20loaded%20ghost%20gun%20(unserialized)%20was%20recovered%20in%20the%20car.\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933150]\n+  - test_id: 36\n+    desc: \"False Positive: phpinfo being used in english sentence\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=Moreover,%20phpinfo%20can%20potentially%20leak%20sensitive%20configuration%20details%20that%20an%20attacker%20can%20exploit%20to%20gain%20information%20about%20the%20server.\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933150]\n+  - test_id: 37\n+    desc: \"False Positive: `intval` substring false positive\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=PaintValdosta\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933150]\n+  - test_id: 38\n+    desc: \"True Positive: match open parenthesis\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get/?test=base64_decode(\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [933150]\n+  - test_id: 39\n+    desc: \"True Positive: match encoded parenthesis\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: GET\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/get/?test=base64_decode%28\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [933150]\ndiff --git a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933160.yaml b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933160.yaml\nindex 0d2dcfeb66..07608bce5f 100644\n--- a/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933160.yaml\n+++ b/tests/regression/tests/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP/933160.yaml\n@@ -795,3 +795,99 @@ tests:\n         output:\n           log:\n             expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 45\n+    desc: \"False Positive: `unserialize` substring false positive\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=A%20loaded%20ghost%20gun%20(unserialized)%20was%20recovered%20in%20the%20car.\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 46\n+    desc: \"False Positive: phpinfo being used in english sentence\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=Moreover,%20phpinfo%20can%20potentially%20leak%20sensitive%20configuration%20details%20that%20an%20attacker%20can%20exploit%20to%20gain%20information%20about%20the%20server.\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 47\n+    desc: \"False Positive: `intval` substring false positive\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=PaintValdosta\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            no_expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 48\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block intval function\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=intval(foo)\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 49\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block phpinfo function\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=phpinfo(foo)\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [933160]\n+  - test_id: 50\n+    desc: \"True Positive: Block unserialize function\"\n+    stages:\n+      - input:\n+          dest_addr: 127.0.0.1\n+          headers:\n+            Host: localhost\n+            User-Agent: \"OWASP CRS test agent\"\n+            Accept: text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5\n+          method: POST\n+          port: 80\n+          uri: \"/post/?test=unserialize(foo)\"\n+          version: \"HTTP/1.1\"\n+        output:\n+          log:\n+            expect_ids: [933160]\n", "problem_statement": "Rule 933150 Has False Positive for PHP Functions in Substrings\n### Description\n\nFrom https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/issues/3641#issuecomment-3525344886.\n\nRule 933150 flags substrings for PHP functions. For example, `intval` in \"PaintValdosta\". This is particularly an issue with URLs where multiple words are concatenated.\n\n### How to reproduce the misbehavior (-> curl call)\n\n```sh\ncurl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org/PaintValdosta\n```\n\n```\n933150 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: High-Risk PHP Function Name Found\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 5)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=5, detection=5, per_pl=5-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=0, PHPI=5, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=5)\n```\n\n### Confirmation\n\n[X] I have removed any personal data (email addresses, IP addresses,\n    passwords, domain names) from any logs posted.\n\n", "hints_text": "@EsadCetiner That\u2019s the issue I\u2019m raising regarding the redistribution of datasets based on false-positive risk.\n\nThis particular set is one of those I plan to split. Sequences shorter than 5 characters should be isolated, as well as those shorter than 7 characters that match `[\\w\\/]+.`\n\nIf you want another FP : saintvalentin.jpg\n\n", "all_hints_text": "@EsadCetiner That\u2019s the issue I\u2019m raising regarding the redistribution of datasets based on false-positive risk.\n\nThis particular set is one of those I plan to split. Sequences shorter than 5 characters should be isolated, as well as those shorter than 7 characters that match `[\\w\\/]+.`\n\nIf you want another FP : saintvalentin.jpg\n@ssigwart I've opened a PR at #4340 which should resolve this issue.\n> If you want another FP : saintvalentin.jpg\n\nGood one.\n\n> [@ssigwart](https://github.com/ssigwart) I've opened a PR at [#4340](https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/pull/4340) which should resolve this issue.\n\nThanks, @EsadCetiner. Looking at https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/blob/main/rules/php-function-names-933150.data, here are some other false positives that I can think of:\n\n- `fclose` -> \"SelfCloseDoors\"\n- `fwrite` -> I feel like there could be something here.\n- `getenv` -> \"GetEnvironmentalImpact\"\n\nThey might be a bit contrived, but I wonder if rule 933150 could be adjusted a little instead of moving possible FPs to rule 933160. If seems like rule 933150 should require a boundary character on either side. I see it uses `@pmFromFile` and I don't know much about that, but maybe there's some other function that searches for boundaries.\n@ssigwart \n> here are some other false positives that I can think of:\n\nI see where your coming from and I see the same issue as well, are these actual false positives you encountered? The only reason why I haven't made a bigger change to these rules as it seems like these false positives are relatively small and just edge cases.\n\n> should require a boundary character on either side\n\nYes that's the main issue here\n\n> I see it uses @pmFromFile and I don't know much about that\n\nUnfortunately the `@pmFromFile` operator isn't very flexible, it's pretty much just a simple list. The rule is likely using that operator for performance reasons, iirc there was an attempt to benchmark the performance difference between `@rx` and `@pmFromFile` a while back but nothing has come of it so far. I'm trying to be cautious in terms of performance.\n\"PaintValdosta\" is a real one. The others were just me trying to think of somewhat plausible ones for general use cases. They probably wouldn't impact my site. i did didn't want you to be adding rules specifically for my use cases since I could create custom rules to exclude them.\n\nI wonder if there's some way to use `@pmFromFile` to do the initial match, then chain it to use some other operative like `@rx` to see if it's a boundary. Would it be a performance issue for the rule to have a large `@rx` if it rarely was executed?\n@ssigwart \n\n> I wonder if there's some way to use @pmFromFile to do the initial match, then chain it to use some other operative like @rx to see if it's a boundary. Would it be a performance issue for the rule to have a large @rx if it rarely was executed?\n\nI actually had that idea a few minutes after I posted my comment, I'm taking a look at it now. Checking for a few special characters should be enough. And yes, there shouldn't be any performance issues since the first chained rule will need to match first before the second one runs.\n@ssigwart I've updated my PR to add a chained rule\nThanks, @EsadCetiner. That definitely seems like an improvement to me. I forget exactly what `MATCHED_VARS` returns, but would something like `https://example.com/SelfCloseDoors#details` still be an issue because it has `#`? Actually, would the dots trigger it too?\n\nRegardless, I think it's worth merging your PR. I'm getting into smaller and smaller edge cases.\n> would something like https://example.com/SelfCloseDoors#details still be an issue because it has `#`\n\nYes, since 933160 is checking for those characters (It's also checking for slashes) I added those characters to the chained rule. I don't have much experience with writing PHP code, but looking at 933160 it looks like the parenthesis `()` is the really important part here, I could be wrong so I'm just being cautious. \nI write PHP all the time. I don't think any characters besides `(` and `)` are needed since functions are executed with `()`. One thing that we probably need someone else's feedback on is whether `/get?base64_deCOde` really should be blocked. I think a more realistic URL would be `/get?action=base64_deCOde`. Potentially, if someone used `eval($_GET['action'])` or `$_GET['action']()`, it would be exploitable even though there's no parenthesis. That would be terribly insecure code though, so I don't know if that's what this rule is trying to block or something else.\n\nI also took a look at real attack attempts on the site I manage. Here are a few examples:\n\n```\nGET /?s=../%5Cthink%5CContainer/invokefunction&function=call_user_func_array&vars%5B0%5D=md5&vars%5B1%5D%5B%5D=HelloThinkPHP\n```\n\nI found https://www.akamai.com/blog/security/thinkphp-exploit-actively-exploited-in-the-wild. So it looks like some PHP library had a vulnerability that didn't involve parenthesis.\n\nThe other thing that I see a lot of are requests like these:\n```\nGET /phpinfo\nGET /phpinfo.php\n```\n\n`phpinfo` is a function in PHP to show system information. I think this is a special case though. People often would name a page the same as the function. I think that `phpinfo` could deserve it's own rule for checking the filename so that you don't need to consider it too much in this rule because it's a different animal.\n> I write PHP all the time. I don't think any characters besides ( and ) are needed since functions are executed with (). \n\nThanks for confirming my suspicion, after digging a bit further I think that's all that needs to be checked in the chained rule. I think 933160 is checking for characters such as `#` to take into account evasions, that shouldn't an issue with 933150's chained rule.\n\n> One thing that we probably need someone else's feedback on is whether /get?base64_deCOde really should be blocked\n\nMost CRS rules inspect `ARGS_NAMES`, so there's likely not a specific reason but iirc I have seen attacks specifically within the parameter name.\n\n> Potentially, if someone used eval($_GET['action']) or $_GET['action'](), it would be exploitable even though there's no parenthesis\n\nThese cases are already handled by different rules:\n```\n$ curl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d \"test=eval($_GET['action'])\"\n933160 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: High-Risk PHP Function Call Found\n934100 PL1 Node.js Injection Attack 1/2\n941390 PL1 Javascript method detected\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 15)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=15, detection=15, per_pl=15-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=5, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=5, PHPI=5, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=15)\n```\n\n```\ncurl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d \"test=\\$_GET['action'](a)\"\n933130 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: Variables Found\n933180 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: Variable Function Call Found\n949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 10)\n980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=10, detection=10, per_pl=10-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=0, PHPI=10, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=10)\n```\n\n> I also took a look at real attack attempts on the site I manage. Here are a few examples:\n\nThis payload looks like it's testing for exploitability, and I don't really see how this example could be adapted into something that's actually harmful while also bypassing the other rules. Based on what I'm seeing in the blog post, the actually harmful attacks should be blocked. The PHP injection probably could be a bit better though, can you open an issue for this to look into further? \n\n> phpinfo is a function in PHP to show system information. I think this is a special case though. People often would name a page the same as the function. I think that phpinfo could deserve it's own rule for checking the filename so that you don't need to consider it too much in this rule because it's a different animal.\n\nActually we already added an entry into `restricted-files.data` and friends a few months back, so this should already be covered.\n> > Potentially, if someone used eval($_GET['action']) or $_GET'action', it would be exploitable even though there's no parenthesis\n> \n> These cases are already handled by different rules:\n> \n> ```\n> $ curl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d \"test=eval($_GET['action'])\"\n> 933160 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: High-Risk PHP Function Call Found\n> 934100 PL1 Node.js Injection Attack 1/2\n> 941390 PL1 Javascript method detected\n> 949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 15)\n> 980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=15, detection=15, per_pl=15-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=5, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=5, PHPI=5, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=15)\n> ```\n> \n> ```\n> curl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d \"test=\\$_GET['action'](a)\"\n> 933130 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: Variables Found\n> 933180 PL1 PHP Injection Attack: Variable Function Call Found\n> 949110 PL? Inbound Anomaly Score Exceeded (Total Score: 10)\n> 980170 PL? Anomaly Scores: (Inbound Scores: blocking=10, detection=10, per_pl=10-0-0-0, threshold=5) - (Outbound Scores: blocking=0, detection=0, per_pl=0-0-0-0, threshold=4) - (SQLI=0, XSS=0, RFI=0, LFI=0, RCE=0, PHPI=10, HTTP=0, SESS=0, COMBINED_SCORE=10)\n> ```\n\nThese examples are of the attacker posting `eval($_GET['action'])` and `$_GET['action'](a)`. I was saying that the way that I think an attacker posting `action=some_php_function` would be an issue is if the website that they targeted had code that ran `eval($_GET['action'])` or `$_GET['action']()`, which would be a terrible idea. The `curl` test would be this:\n```sh\ncurl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d 'action=phpversion'\n```\n\nI don't think the PR will block that anymore and I just want to be cautious in case people are relying on that.\n\n> The PHP injection probably could be a bit better though, can you open an issue for this to look into further?\n\nSorry, I'm not sure exactly what you're referring to here.\n> I don't think the PR will block that anymore and I just want to be cautious in case people are relying on that.\n\nThese attacks weren't being picked up by 933150 in the first place, so there'll be no change in that regard.\n\n> Sorry, I'm not sure exactly what you're referring to here.\n\nI meant on matching naked PHP functions like `phpversion`, since you've showed a few examples of this being exploitable. The existing rules don't take this case into consideration.\nI may be missing something, but the following shows that rule 933150 is triggered.\n```sh\ncurl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org -d 'action=phpversion'\n```\n\nAlso, in #4340, I see that you changed tests like `uri: \"/get/base64_decode\"` to `uri: \"/get/?test=base64_decode()\"`. I assume that's because it no longer triggered without the parenthesis.\n@EsadCetiner, I was thinking that the key here is to try to quickly match the PHP functions, but not a substring. This could be a crazy idea, but what do you think of the process below? I'm not entirely clear on what's possibly with the rules.\n\n1. Do the `@pmFromFile` like normal.\n2. Chain it to a rule that uses a regular expression to split it into words, then uses the md5 transform on each rule.\n3. Do `@pmFromFile` on each match (now an MD5) using a file that is the MD5 of the lines in `rules/php-function-names-933150.data`.\n> I may be missing something, but the following shows that rule 933150 is triggered.\n\nYes you are right, but that was more [accidental rather than intentional](https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/blob/e57b677877822aa9ce5d1b02f25ef644a5e2637d/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf#L312) per the comments for 933150. 933150 only includes a limited amount of PHP functions, generally longer function names that are less likely to cause false positives.\n\n> Also, in https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/pull/4340, I see that you changed tests like uri: \"/get/base64_decode\" to uri: \"/get/?test=base64_decode()\". I assume that's because it no longer triggered without the parenthesis.\n\nYes, because the rule is no longer looking for a purely naked php function.\n\n> what do you think of the process below? I'm not entirely clear on what's possibly with the rules.\n\nSorry, I don't follow, I'm not sure how using the md5 transformation here would be useful, although this issue isn't specific to 933150.\nThat makes more sense. It's not that it didn't detect them before. It's that that wasn't the intent. Sounds good.\n\nFor the MD5 transformations, my understanding is that, in general, `@pmFromFile` is preferred because it is fast, but the downside is that it is a substring match. There are places where it would be better for a rule to match full words. So I was thinking that if `@pmFromFile` was used for a quick test to see if there's a substring, a chain could be use to do a more thorough check for the full work. If the chain could split the match into words and then do an MD5 on the words (maybe lowercase words), the comparison of the MD5 to an MD5 list with `@pmFromFile` would be fast and eliminate false positives.\n\nFor example, with the `PaintValdosta` example, it would compare the MD5 of `paintvaldosta` (`4feae1dc3fa8cb1b20788c8b5709e23f`) with that of `intval` (`fb42920bc738a35518e3109fc5b51dc6`) and since they don't match, it would know that it wasn't a full substring match.\n\nAnother option would be to add a chain after `@pmFromFile` to do an `@rx` of the same function list, but with boundary conditions similar to this:\nhttps://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/blob/e57b677877822aa9ce5d1b02f25ef644a5e2637d/rules/REQUEST-933-APPLICATION-ATTACK-PHP.conf#L373\n\nHowever, I don't know if having a huge `@rx` in the rules config file would have a performance impact. If not, that might be the way to go for rules that want boundary conditions, but wants to do a quick preliminary check with `@pmFromFile`.\n> my understanding is that, in general, @pmFromFile is preferred because it is fast, but the downside is that it is a substring match\n\nYes that's correct.\n\n> If the chain could split the match into words and then do an MD5 on the words (maybe lowercase words), the comparison of the MD5 to an MD5 list with @pmFromFile would be fast and eliminate false positives.\n\nThe MD5 transformation will transform the entire matched parameter, you'd need to use a regex backreference to extract the specific function without any substring matches then add the extra checks. Although backreferences are [not allowed due to ReDoS risk and compatibility with non-backtracking regex engines](https://coreruleset.org/docs/6-development/6-1-contribution-guidelines/#writing-regular-expressions-for-non-backtracking-compatibility) (I see your thought process, but I think you misunderstand how transformations work). 933150 doesn't include all PHP functions, so naked functions like `fputs` or `fopen` will still be affected by said issue even if this worked as we expected hypothetically.\n\n> However, I don't know if having a huge @rx in the rules config file would have a performance impact. If not, that might be the way to go for rules that want boundary conditions, but wants to do a quick preliminary check with @pmFromFile.\n\nI think we'd have to move all the rules to a regex anyways, I don't see a way to do it with the `@pmFromFile` operator at all even with chained rules. It's better if you open another issue to discuss this, and we can handle the false positive issue for this rule for now. This discussion is starting to get a bit off topic anyways.\nYeah, I don't write too many rules, so I don't know exactly how the transformations work.\n\nI'm good with what you have. I personally don't really depend on the ModSecurity rules to prevent attacks. It's main to satisfy PCI compliance requirements, so I'm more concerned with eliminating false positives than protecting against everything. I think your PR will solve most false positives.\n\nThanks!\n> * `fwrite` -> I feel like there could be something here.\n\nThis came up in the wild today for me as part of an email address input, but I don't want to share the email, so here's a URL alongs the same lines that get's blocked:\n\n```\ncurl -H \"x-format-output: txt-matched-rules\" https://sandbox.coreruleset.org/JeffWritesBooks\n```\n@ssigwart Thanks, this should be handled by #4340 \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/2f6d0e364d394fc9aa1675ed0c88af546452f9e8", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/5532d061910338a51d4a446c02cc182b3af00b40", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/f5d2eeb0dd761ada71fd5ea1703647f13c6bdfbb", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/f0f3f841fa613a46c70007938b7d9804046a79e0", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/df0c8741a50e2050f0b77ad4c92de327dc18f261", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/be6b1bc811e5a0cd84dbe336569bcb06fe5aa59e", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/8b88b7449aa5dbeb4bdf03eaf7b9a89f89156f77", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/306c48f9249f145a2ad0da4a1728a9d35f3ed770", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/cc5eb0dd06b2e62d99d4ca7b6c3639087924e4c3", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/108461827039e6e265e6dd797ced7096a5e25219", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/04b168e3c2fd82be380ba89201cc0e72c64a0a08", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/a0d8164199ad5359092781cad45a0d2b49e94f98", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/4c66251e085c6118f2330cfeb5077e95b878ebd1", "https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/cfc01dd1fc583a229cd53e0d60874a9109c52956"], "created_at": "2025-11-14T09:58:05Z"}
{"repo": "coreruleset/coreruleset", "pull_number": 4344, "instance_id": "coreruleset__coreruleset-4344", "issue_numbers": [4343], "base_commit": "dc9a2683f1a73ee5ed31e819f1828dcb2b814237", "patch": "diff --git a/rules/RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY.conf b/rules/RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY.conf\nindex af4c21e368..8259ebcf31 100644\n--- a/rules/RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY.conf\n+++ b/rules/RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY.conf\n@@ -53,10 +53,16 @@ SecRule RESPONSE_BODY \"@pmFromFile ruby-errors.data\" \\\n     setvar:'tx.outbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.error_anomaly_score}'\"\n \n \n+SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 2\" \"id:956013,phase:3,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n+SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 2\" \"id:956014,phase:4,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n+\n+\n # Detect the presence of the Ruby ERB templates \"<%\", \"<%= \" and slim interpolation \"#{}\" in output.\n #\n # To prevent false positives (due to the short \"<%\" sequences), we also check for [#=\\s] after an opening tag.\n #\n+# This rule is placed at PL-2 since it also matches common templating format with various JavaScript templating engines.\n+#\n SecRule RESPONSE_BODY \"@rx (?i)(?:<%[=#\\s]|#\\{[^}]+\\})\" \\\n     \"id:956110,\\\n     phase:4,\\\n@@ -69,18 +75,13 @@ SecRule RESPONSE_BODY \"@rx (?i)(?:<%[=#\\s]|#\\{[^}]+\\})\" \\\n     tag:'language-ruby',\\\n     tag:'platform-multi',\\\n     tag:'attack-disclosure',\\\n-    tag:'paranoia-level/1',\\\n+    tag:'paranoia-level/2',\\\n     tag:'OWASP_CRS',\\\n     tag:'OWASP_CRS/DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY',\\\n     tag:'capec/1000/118/116',\\\n     ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',\\\n     severity:'ERROR',\\\n-    setvar:'tx.outbound_anomaly_score_pl1=+%{tx.error_anomaly_score}'\"\n-\n-\n-SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 2\" \"id:956013,phase:3,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n-SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 2\" \"id:956014,phase:4,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n-\n+    setvar:'tx.outbound_anomaly_score_pl2=+%{tx.error_anomaly_score}'\"\n \n SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 3\" \"id:956015,phase:3,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n SecRule TX:DETECTION_PARANOIA_LEVEL \"@lt 3\" \"id:956016,phase:4,pass,nolog,tag:'OWASP_CRS',ver:'OWASP_CRS/4.21.0-dev',skipAfter:END-RESPONSE-956-DATA-LEAKAGES-RUBY\"\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "False positives with Ruby leakage (956110)\n### Description\n\nI'm experiencing lots of false positives with rule 956110, which is blocking strings `#{...}`. This format is used by various JavaScript templating engines (for example Pug) and is adopted by lots of custom JavaScript software (for example Horde/IMP or Zabbix GUI).\n\n### How to reproduce the misbehavior (-> curl call)\n\nPut one of thse into output:\n\n```\n#{usrgrpid}\n#{time}\n```\n### Your Environment\n\n<!-- Please provide all relevant information about your environment. -->\n\n* CRS version (e.g., v3.3.4): 4.20.0\n* Paranoia level setting (e.g. PL1) : PL1\n* ModSecurity version (e.g., 2.9.6): 2.9\n* Web Server and version or cloud provider / CDN (e.g., Apache httpd 2.4.54): Apache\n* Operating System and version: Debian 11\n\n### Confirmation\n\n[x] I have removed any personal data (email addresses, IP addresses,\n    passwords, domain names) from any logs posted.\n\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "@azurit Since the syntax is the same, I've proposed moving this rule to PL-2 in #4344\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/coreruleset/coreruleset/commit/2403da38b813d405075b0b2883a5de554bcd944a"], "created_at": "2025-11-17T02:33:01Z"}
